<h2>What this is</h2>
<p>You will write the <strong>Landscape Biography</strong> of one Chennai-area location — what made it the way it is, what's actively shaping it now, and what it could look like in 50 years under three different scenarios. The audience is a hypothetical Greater Chennai Corporation planning meeting. Your job is to give planners something they can <em>act on</em>.</p>

<h2>Three deliverable formats — same rubric</h2>
<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">Choose one format</div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Written report</strong> — Google Doc or PDF, ≤1500 words.</li>
    <li><strong>Annotated Google Earth video</strong> — screen-record yourself narrating Google Earth navigation, ≤6 min, fully captioned.</li>
    <li><strong>Large infographic</strong> — single visual with all sections visible. Canva, Adobe Express, or Google Drawings.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Same rubric, same expectations, same components. Pick the one that lets your landscape-reading thinking come through clearest. Format choice is locked with Mr. Ignash by Block 5.</p>
</div>

<h2>The nine location options</h2>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Location</th><th>Category</th><th>Why it's interesting</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Cooum River basin</td><td>Urban river</td><td>Heavily modified; restoration underway. Lots of news + government coverage — strong OPVL diversity.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Adyar River + Estuary</td><td>Urban river / coastal</td><td>Restoration project; estuary ecologically critical and contested. Cross-process analysis (river ↔ coastal).</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Marina Beach</td><td>Coastal</td><td>One of the world's longest urban beaches. Coastal erosion + monsoon-driven sediment cycling. Most accessible option.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Pulicat Lagoon</td><td>Coastal wetland</td><td>Brackish lagoon north of Chennai; flamingo habitat; industrial-development conflict. Less media coverage = harder, more rewarding OPVL.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Mahabalipuram coast</td><td>Coastal / heritage</td><td>UNESCO site. Rock-cut temples on 1300-Mya granite. Excellent for deep-time + human-time analysis.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Eastern Ghats foothills</td><td>Inland hills</td><td>Tropical weathering, inselbergs, ancient temple geology. Different process suite (not coastal).</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Buckingham Canal</td><td>Anthropogenic canal</td><td>Artificial canal cutting through coastal landscape, partly silted up. Strong human-modification focus.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Red Hills / Sholavaram Lake</td><td>Reservoir / water supply</td><td>Chennai's main drinking-water reservoir. Anthropogenic + natural interactions. Strong policy relevance.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>AISC campus walk</td><td>In-class fallback</td><td>Analyse campus drainage, soil, exposed rock. Tightly bounded scope; most accessible for students who want simplicity.</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p>International students (or anyone without Chennai connection) may propose a non-listed location with Mr. Ignash's approval — case-by-case, if well-studied online and OPVL-feasible.</p>

<h2>Required components (any format)</h2>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Landscape biography (past)</strong> — the sequence of processes that created what we see today.</li>
  <li><strong>Current-processes section</strong> — 3–4 active processes shaping the location <em>now</em>.</li>
  <li><strong>50-year projections under 3 scenarios</strong> — status quo · increased monsoon variability · sea-level rise (or equivalent local stressor).</li>
  <li><strong>Recommendations for monitoring or protection</strong> — 3–5 concrete, evidence-based, audience-appropriate items.</li>
  <li><strong>AI Documentation Template</strong> — required if you used AI at any stage (almost everyone will, via the Field Geologist).</li>
  <li><strong>Class share-out</strong> — 3-minute presentation + 2-minute planner Q&A in Block 9.</li>
</ol>

<h2>What you'll be scored on</h2>
<p>The Landscape Reading does triple duty: it assesses unit content (surface processes, geomorphology, monsoon, Chennai geography), it exercises <a href="/foundations/opvl-framework/">OPVL</a> on geological + cartographic sources, and it launches science-policy-public communication (Thread 4). The planning-audience share-out in Block 9 is the C-strand component of the rubric.</p>

<p>Grade weighting: Landscape Reading 70% · Class share-out 15% · Formative work (Blocks 1–4 activities, OPVL practice, peer feedback) 15%.</p>

<h2>AI Documentation</h2>
<p>If you use the <a href="/ai-partners/field-geologist/">Field Geologist</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/the-source-evaluator/">Source Evaluator</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/the-skeptic/">Skeptic</a>, or any other AI tool while working on this assessment, the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a> is required. Same rules as Units 0 and 1: every substantive AI conversation gets documented; the "one thing the AI got wrong" gate applies.</p>

